I absolutely love this idea.

It’s basically Where’s Waldo? meets shark tooth hunting meets beachcombing, and it actually teaches people to identify real shark teeth while they’re playing.

Shark Tooth Odyssey

A Search & Find Adventure

Format

* 6 oversized, highly detailed two-page beach spreads.
* Photorealistic style (not cartoon).
* Every grain of sand, shell, pebble, driftwood fragment, seaweed, crab, and wave rendered in incredible detail.
* Hundreds of believable objects per page.

The objective is to find real shark teeth hidden naturally among shells and pebbles—not placed obviously.

⸻

Page 1 — Venice Beach

“Shark Tooth Capital”  

Easy introduction.

Find:

* 12 sand tiger teeth
* 5 bull shark teeth
* 2 tiger shark teeth
* one tiny megalodon fragment

Background:

* shell piles
* kids digging
* ghost crabs
* pelicans
* surf foam

⸻

Page 2 — Caspersen Beach

More shell hash.

Objects become much harder.

Some teeth are:

* broken
* partially buried
* upside down
* mixed with black phosphate pebbles

Hidden challenge:
Find one complete juvenile great white tooth.

⸻

Page 3 — Folly Beach

Lots of fossils mixed into shell beds.  

Find:

* shark teeth
* stingray mouth plates
* fish vertebrae
* whale bone fragment

Introduce a field guide sidebar explaining how to distinguish real teeth from shells.

⸻

Page 4 — Cherry Grove Beach

Incoming tide.

Everything glistening.

Many teeth only visible from tiny triangular silhouettes.

Wave foam hides portions of objects.

⸻

Page 5 — Wrightsville Beach

After-storm conditions.  

Dark shell line.

Large debris.

Driftwood.

Sea glass.

Hidden:

* tiny mako tooth
* hammerhead tooth
* dozens of worn fragments

⸻

Page 6 — “The Megalodon Storm”

Inspired by several famous East Coast fossil beaches.

The tide has uncovered an enormous shell bed.

Hundreds of shark teeth.

Only ONE complete museum-quality megalodon tooth.

It isn’t obvious.

It’s partially hidden beneath shells.

The reader has learned enough by now to actually recognize it.

⸻

Bonus Mechanics

Instead of simply saying:

Find 12 shark teeth.

The game becomes progressive.

Level 1:
Find anything triangular.

↓

Level 2:
Identify:

* sand tiger
* bull
* lemon
* tiger
* mako
* great white

↓

Level 3:
Determine:

* modern or fossil?
* worn or pristine?
* left or right jaw?

Kids accidentally learn paleontology while playing.

⸻

My favorite addition

Don’t make every page static.

Hide cycles.

The same piece of driftwood appears on every beach.

A little sandpiper travels through every spread.

One shell slowly breaks apart across the pages.

The tide advances.

Clouds change.

The light shifts.

A child who found one tiny shark tooth on page one proudly carries their growing collection through the rest of the book.

The reader begins by searching for objects.

By the last page, they’re recognizing patterns.

That’s the Oshawa Crossing of the book.

They don’t just get better at the game.

They become a different kind of observer. 🤜🤛